image.altText: Emil Petrov wears a black waterproof jacket over a cream coloured shirt and has brown rimmed glasses resting on his forehead.

props.synopsis: A trial has begun for Emil "Bill" Petrov who has pleaded not guilty to killing Cindy Crossthwaite in her Melton South home in 2007.

title.children: Prosecutors allege man bought gun and asked a friend to help kill his estranged wife

image.altText: Tactical police officers stand on a roof in Weir Views.

props.synopsis: Police exchanged fire with an armed man at Weir Views in Melbourne's outer west on Tuesday, with the gunman locking himself into the home of an unsuspecting family.

title.children: Man caught in the crossfire of Melbourne police siege along with his infant son thanks his rescuers

image.altText: Three men vote at a polling station in Hobart, Tasmania.

props.synopsis: A suspicious number of multiple returns — defined as more than one postal ballot pack returned from a single voter — were flagged in Whittlesea City Council Lalor Ward and Knox City Council Baird Ward elections.

title.children: Legitimacy of two Victorian council elections in question after duplicate votes detected

image.altText: A pig seen lying on the ground at a piggery.

props.synopsis: A court has heard that footage of a Carag Carag man allegedly committing a sexual act against a pig should be considered inadmissible because it was illegally obtained.

title.children: Defence says alleged bestiality footage inadmissible because it was illegally taken

image.altText: A church building with a cross shrouded under branches

props.synopsis: The Catholic Church wins a High Court appeal against rulings it was vicariously liable for the actions of a priest who allegedly sexually abused a five-year-old in 1971.

title.children: Catholic Church wins High Court appeal against ruling it was vicariously liable for alleged sexual abuse by a priest

image.altText: A man in a suit outside of a court house

props.synopsis: An ABC investigation has uncovered a disturbing escalation in rhetoric from prominent neo-Nazis in Australia, including comments about encouraging violent crime.

title.children: 'Touch our kids, it's over': Neo-Nazi issues chilling warning to authorities

image.altText: Flowers outside a school

props.synopsis: Australia's leading injury prevention organisation says bollards, barriers, and rocks should be placed around schools and playgrounds to help stop vehicles crossing roadsides and footpaths.

title.children: Call for changes to infrastructure around schools after tragic deaths in Victoria

image.altText: A person looking at images of women in bikinis on a computer

props.synopsis: A report by Our Watch has revealed the average teenage Australian girl has viewed pornography before her 14th birthday, with fears it is becoming a default source of sexual education for children.

title.children: Young people encountering porn earlier than ever and using it for sex education, new report finds

image.altText: Donald Trump sits in court in a suit and red tie looking at the camera

props.synopsis: In the days since his election win, Donald Trump has moved to have his felony convictions in the New York hush money case dismissed, with a decision now expected next week.

title.children: 'These are unprecedented circumstances': Trump's new move to dismiss convictions

image.altText: A digital board with multiple rows reading "cancelled".

props.synopsis: Jetstar, Qantas and Virgin Australia have cancelled flights to and from Bali until at least Wednesday afternoon.

title.children: Flights to and from Bali cancelled after volcanic eruption creates thick ash cloud

image.altText: A man on a bike rides through the street with ruins of buildings behind him

props.synopsis: Some 50,000 Russian troops have reportedly moved to a region held by Ukraine since August, with experts saying it is no coincidence that the renewed interest coincides with the US presidential race and the re-election of Donald Trump.

title.children: Russia wants Ukraine's 'bargaining chip' before Donald Trump returns to the White House

image.altText: A man with short hair sits in front of a microphone, looking serious.

props.synopsis: The Breakfast host announces he is ready to trade the early alarm for more regular hours after five years of waking up Melbourne.

title.children: Sammy J to leave ABC Radio Melbourne Breakfast role after five years

image.altText: A large truck carrying pallets of aid bundles through a dusty border crossing.

props.synopsis: The US will continue to provide military assistance to the Netanyahu government, despite aid agencies saying it has fallen short of providing enough aid to the wartorn region.

title.children: Aid agencies accuse Israel of failing to provide enough support to Gaza as US deadline passes

image.altText: A phone displaying the meta logo sits on a computer keyboard

props.synopsis: This year's Shonky Awards have been announced, with Facebook parent company Meta amongst the winners for its "inadequate action" against scams.

title.children: The five 'shonkiest' products and companies put in the spotlight in annual CHOICE consumer awards

image.altText: A digital tablet is attached to a shopping trolley.

props.synopsis: Woolworths says it wants to roll out its smart shopping trolleys to more stores to help people budget their shops better. Smart carts overseas have helped increase the average customer spend by 6 per cent.

title.children: The tech company behind Woolworths 'smart' shopping trolleys says they could help you buy more impulsively

image.altText: A lady with pink hair stands in front a clearing of bushland where a blue tent stands in the background.

props.synopsis: Castlemaine is one of 68 locations across Australia with a rental vacancy rate of less than 1 per cent. There are said to be 600 people who need a house in the region, yet only 10 homes are listed for lease online.

title.children: In the popular Victorian commuter town of Castlemaine, there are only 10 homes available to rent

image.altText: Jy Simpkin leads players off Perth Stadium

props.synopsis: North Melbourne will play six home games in Western Australia over the next three seasons in a deal that will provide significant financial benefit to the club.

title.children: North Melbourne to play four 'home' games outside of Victoria for 2025 season

image.altText: Composite image of six victims of jumping castle tragedy with school signage as background

props.synopsis: An engineer says having all available anchor points secured on a jumping castle may not have prevented it becoming airborne — but still, not enough was done to ensure safety before six children died in 2021.

title.children: Engineer says Hillcrest jumping castle may still have become airborne even if all anchors were used

image.altText: A composite image of the Rainbow Warrior, Rongelap Atoll and a nuclear explosion

props.synopsis: The Rainbow Warrior made headlines around the world when it was sunk by French operatives. But before that, its lesser-known last mission was to evacuate an entire island poisoned by nuclear testing in the Pacific.

title.children: US nuclear testing forced an entire island in the Pacific to evacuate — onboard a Greenpeace ship

image.altText: The outside of the County Court of Victoria building.

props.synopsis: Mohamed Ahmed Omer was found guilty of secretly withdrawing support for his former wife's visa application before abandoning her on an overseas trip.

title.children: Victorian man jailed for four and a half years after abandoning former wife in Sudan

image.altText: A hand holding several cigarettes

props.synopsis: The Victorian government will establish a new tobacco regulator, introduce a licensing scheme and give police more powers as part of new measures to combat the state's illegal tobacco trade.

title.children: Victorian government introduces new laws and licensing as it tries to end the state's tobacco wars

image.altText: A small child's hand is cupped by an old woman's hand

props.synopsis: One in three Australian grandparents babysit their grandkids to fill in gaps in childcare, becoming a support "village" for working parents, research finds. But what happens if you don't have grandparents to rely on?

title.children: What happens when you don't have a 'village' or grandparents to help with childcare?

image.altText: The exterior of a Commonwealth Bank branchm including the brand's logos.

props.synopsis: Wages growth has slowed to 3.5 per cent over the past year, but continues to outpace inflation. Meanwhile, a fall on Wall Street has sent Australian stocks sharply lower. Look back at the day's events.

title.children: Wages growth slows, CBA logs flat first-quarter profit, ASX falls — as it happened

image.altText: A Korean woman with short hair sitting at desk wearing Kodak yellow fleece.

props.synopsis: The radical feminist 4B movement took root in a culture where women face domestic violence and insidious spy-cam sexploitation, as well as the "double burden" of work and family.

title.children: Women in the US are joining a 'sex strike', but in Korea, 4B is a radical way of living

image.altText: A stressed-looking woman with short gray hair and maroon top sitting at a table with her head in her hand.

props.synopsis: First results of the 2024 National Carers Survey show many carers feel socially isolated and suffer from high or very high levels of psychological distress.

title.children: 'I've pretty much given up': Stressed and isolated carers say they can't get the support they need

image.altText: A row of people looking at their phones with one set of hands and phone in focus.

props.synopsis: The federal government wants to create powers to curb the spread of misinformation and outright lies online. But legal experts have detailed why they worry that the proposed laws could actually undermine the truth.

title.children: Scientists at first misunderstood how COVID spread. Under proposed laws, the truth could have been struck from the internet

image.altText: University students walk through campus, some looking at their phones. The photo is blurry, making faces unidentifiable.

props.synopsis: As the Albanese government moves to ease the debt burden in the HECS system, a different group of former students is demanding their debt be wiped.

title.children: 'Life sentence': The government 'debt trap' Australians are still paying back

image.altText: Former actor Orpheus Pledger wears a cap and a face mask as he departs from the County Court of Victoria in Melbourne

props.synopsis: Orpheus Pledger, the former Home and Away actor who bashed a woman during a drug-fuelled attack, succeeds in an appeal to reduce his jail sentence.

title.children: Former Home and Away star who bashed woman has jail sentence reduced

image.altText: Two players reach out and try to grab the ball

props.synopsis: Despite winning two international titles this year, the Australian men's netball team is making more headlines for its dance moves. That's after players copped backlash when a video of them copying Deadpool's NSYNC Bye Bye Bye went viral.

title.children: 'You can't compare it to the haka': Australian men's Fast5 captain hits back at homophobic comments

image.altText: A security person stands guard near a sports center where a man rammed a car into a crowd of people.

props.synopsis: Local police describe the hit-and-run incident as a "vicious" and deliberate attack. They say the alleged 62-year-old driver was upset about his divorce.

title.children: 35 killed and 43 others injured in southern China after car deliberately ploughs into crowd

image.altText: A man in a black suit and a yellow tie stands at a podium, addressing the press and gesturing to the crowd.

props.synopsis: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese is moving aggressively to ready Labor for an early election campaign, flying to Tasmania to announce high-profile candidates for Braddon and Lyons.

title.children: Early election speculation reaches a fever pitch as Albanese announces two candidates in two hours

image.altText: A photo of the Shell company logo.

props.synopsis: Oil giant Shell wins a landmark case at The Hague, overturning an earlier court ruling ordering it to cut its carbon emissions by 45 per cent.

title.children: 'We are pleased': Oil giant Shell wins landmark climate case against green groups in Dutch appeal

image.altText: A man and woman leave a building with jackets covering their eyes.

props.synopsis: A mother accused of starving her malnourished daughter has told a Perth court the teenager was "perfect" and had always been thin.

title.children: Malnourished dancer's diet included salad wraps and chocolate, mother accused of starving her tells trial
